## Thesis Core Rules (Always Apply)

### Truth + reproducibility
- Never fabricate numbers, results, citations, dataset sizes, or benchmarks.
- If something is unknown, explicitly mark it as unknown and propose how to measure it.
- Any new experiment code must:
  - accept `--seed`
  - log config + seed
  - write metrics to a machine-readable file (JSON)
  - save a short run summary (markdown or txt)

### Code hygiene
- Prefer clear, boring code over clever code.
- Don’t add dependencies unless necessary. If added, justify in PR text.
- Avoid “magic constants”: promote to config.

### Tracking
- Work should map to an issue/PR. If user asks “do X”, respond with an issue checklist mindset:
  - definition of done
  - files to touch
  - tests / smoke check

### Output discipline
- `runs/` is output-only and should be gitignored.
- Keep `docs/` up-to-date when behavior changes.
